"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862259","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-19","<p>Following the commencement of the National Health Service (Charges to Overseas Visitors) (Amendment) Regulations 2017, in line with the continuing public sector equalities duty, and also recognising concerns that have been raised by stakeholders regarding the introduction of the amendment regulations, the Department committed in November 2017 to review the impact of the changes introduced by the amendment regulations.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is currently working with arm’s length bodies and stakeholders to review the impact of the amendment regulations in respect of upfront charging, patient records, community services and non-NHS providers, with a particular focus on the extent to which there are any unintended consequences on delivery of care for the most vulnerable, and how any such unintended consequences could be addressed.</p><p> </p><p>The Department will provide an update once the review is complete and will set out any further action that is considered necessary following the review.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold information on patients who have been provided with cancer treatment.</p><p> </p><p>A British citizen who is ordinarily resident in the United Kingdom is entitled to receive free NHS healthcare services as long as they can prove they are in the UK lawfully, adopted voluntary and for settled purposes as part of the regular order of his or her life for the time being, whether of short or long duration. This may also require the granting of Indefinite Leave to Remain status, if an individual arrives in the UK from outside of the European Economic Area.</p><p> </p><p>All patients must be assessed against the test for ordinary residence in the UK which will determine whether a patient is ordinarily resident in the UK. If the patient is ordinarily resident in the UK they must not be individually charged.</p><p> </p><p>It is the duty of the NHS providing treatment to establish if charges apply to people who are not ordinarily resident (‘overseas visitors’) for the services they provide and to make and recover any charges.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","132676 ; 132677","2018-03-19T17:34:59.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862259/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862259/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","NHS (Charges to Overseas Visitors) (Amendment) Regulations 2017","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what powers he has to intervene in cases where long-term British residents are denied cancer care as a result of the introduction of the NHS (Charges to Overseas Visitors) (Amendment) Regulations 2017.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","132678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862260","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-19","<p>We are concerned about a number of proposed amendments to the Indonesian penal code, including on potential criminalisation of homosexual and extramarital relations.</p><p>The Minister for the Commonwealth and the UN, Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon, raised our concerns around the revision of the penal code with the Indonesian Ambassador on 22 January. The UK Ambassador to Indonesia also raised our concerns with Minister Laoly, Minister for Law and Human Rights, on 31 January; with individual parliamentarians involved in the drafting on 13 February; and with President Joko Widodo’s Chief of Staff on 12 March.</p><p>​</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2018-03-19T15:42:22.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862260/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862260/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-14","Indonesia: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his counterpart in Indonesia on the potential criminalisation of LGBT acts and extramarital relations by that country's Parliament.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","132679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862261","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-19","<p>We are concerned by the decision of the Government of the Philippines to withdraw the Philippines from the Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court (ICC). Our Embassy in Manila is raising concerns with the Administration. The ICC has an important role to play in ending impunity for the most serious crimes of international concern by holding perpetrators to account and achieving justice for victims. ​</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2018-03-19T15:44:45.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862261/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862261/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-14","Philippines: International Criminal Court","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs what recent representations he has made to his counterpart in the Philippines on the potential withdrawal of that country from the Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","132680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862262","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-22","<p>Government is carefully considering the recommendations made by the Review of Full Time Social Action. I will be meeting with the Chair of the Review to discuss the report as part of this process. The Government response to the review’s report will be published in due course.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-03-22T14:28:45.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862262/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862262/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862262/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-03-14","Youth Social Action Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what plans the Minister of Sport and Civil Society has to meet with the Chair of the Independent review of full-time social action following that report's publication.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","132681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862263","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-19","<p>The trial of 10,000 26-30 railcards is an industry-led initiative to gather evidence and to inform discussions between Government and industry about roll-out of the railcard. Delivery of the trial launch, including sales of the railcard, was led by Rail Delivery Group and it was their digital systems that handled transactions and enquiries on the day.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-03-19T14:16:32.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862263/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862263/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862263/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-14","Railways: Concessions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people were attempting to obtain a 26 to 30 railcard when the website crashed on 13 March 2018.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","132682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862264","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-21","<p>No such estimate has been made.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital collects data on the Hospital and Community Health Service workforce, including nurses working in secondary care organisations and the General and Personal Medical Services workforce, including general practitioners and nurses working in general practices.</p><p> </p><p>However, these data do not enable NHS Digital to assess how much time is spent on any particular task by a member of the National Health Service workforce.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-03-21T12:11:46.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862264/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862264/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862264/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Health Professions: Bureaucracy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the average number of hours spent on administrative tasks each week by (a) nurses and (b) GPs in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","132683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862265","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-22","<p>Farming subsidies are covered by the World Trade Organisation (WTO) Agreement on Agriculture which was adopted by WTO members (including the UK) in 1994. This agreement sets out conditions under which domestic support in favour of agricultural producers may be made. More information can be found on the WTO website:</p><p><a href="https://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/agric_e/ag_intro03_domestic_e.htm" target="_blank">https://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/agric_e/ag_intro03_domestic_e.htm</a>.</p><p>Individual WTO members’ commitments can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/agric_e/supporting_tables_e.htm" target="_blank">https://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/agric_e/supporting_tables_e.htm</a></p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-03-22T10:45:07.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862265/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862265/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862265/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-14","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what information his Department holds on what the maximum amount is that a national government can spend on farming subsidies according to World Trade Organisation rules.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","132684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862266","Home Office","false","2018-03-21","<p>I am the co-chair of the National Retail Crime Steering Group with the British Retail Consortium. It is an important group that brings together representatives from government departments, the police and the retail sector to focus on the crime issues that affect retailers. The Steering Group has a work plan that has been developed in consultation with its members. This helps to ensure that the work is focused on the retail sector’s crime priorities, such as tackling violence and abuse against retail staff.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-03-21T14:39:47.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862266/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862266/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862266/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-14","National Retail Crime Steering Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress her Department has made on helping develop a five-year strategy for the National Retail Crime Steering Group.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","132685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862267","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-21","<p>In September 2017, of those general practitioners (GPs) whose ages are known, 33.2% of GPs were 50 years of age or older. In terms of full-time equivalents, 33.5% of GP FTEs were aged 50 or over.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-21T12:16:07.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862267/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862267/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862267/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","General Practitioners: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what proportion of GPs in England are over 50 years old.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","132686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862268","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-27","<p>I have reprioritised my Department’s existing integration funding over the next two years to directly support the objectives of the new Integrated Communities Strategy Green Paper.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-03-27T16:03:17.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862268/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862268/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862268/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Community Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, from which Departmental funding stream will the £50 million integration fund outlined by the Secretary of State on 14 March 2018, be allocated from.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","132687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862269","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-22","<p>The Department commissions NHS Employers to provide advice, guidance and good practice to employers on all aspects of improving the physical and mental health and wellbeing of their staff. This includes “supporting staff with mental health problems”<sup>1</sup> which includes a “return to work” section.</p><p> </p><p>Note:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><sup>1</sup><a href="http://www.nhsemployers.org/your-workforce/retain-and-improve/staff-experience/health-work-and-wellbeing/protecting-staff-and-preventing-ill-health/supporting-line-managers/managers-guide-on-supporting-workplace-mental-health/supporting-staff-who-are-experiencing-mental-health-problems" target="_blank">http://www.nhsemployers.org/your-workforce/retain-and-improve/staff-experience/health-work-and-wellbeing/protecting-staff-and-preventing-ill-health/supporting-line-managers/managers-guide-on-supporting-workplace-mental-health/supporting-staff-who-are-experiencing-mental-health-problems</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-03-22T12:07:47.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862269/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862269/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862269/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what guidance his Department provides to employers on supporting employees who return to work after a period of mental illness.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","132688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862270","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-22","<p>To help ensure people receive the appropriate care for their clinical needs, the Department’s Refocusing the Care Programme Approach guidance published in 2008 states that exploration of violence and abuse should be routinely undertaken in all mental health assessments. The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guideline on antenatal care for uncomplicated pregnancies also advises appointments should enable women to discuss sensitive issues, including domestic violence and sexual abuse.</p><p> </p><p>In March 2017 the Department published an online Domestic Violence and Abuse resource for health professionals. It advises health staff on how they can support adults and young people over 16 who are experiencing domestic abuse, and dependent children in their households, by showing how they can respond effectively to disclosures of abuse.</p><p> </p><p>In 2017 the Government set up the Women’s Mental Health Taskforce, with the objective of developing proposals and delivering action collaboratively to improve women’s mental health. A core theme running through the work of the Taskforce is engaging women with experience and one of the areas it is exploring is women’s mental health in regard to violence and abuse.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Government announced in March 2018, £2 million funding over the next two years, 2018-19 and 2019-20, to lead the way in creating a model response across health services for survivors of domestic abuse. The funding will support improved identification of domestic abuse across healthcare settings, including consideration of mental health, and will support effective referral to support services.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-03-22T12:11:09.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862270/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862270/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862270/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Mental Health Services: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that mental health services take account of the experiences and needs of women (a) in general and (b) who have experienced extensive abuse.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","132689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862271","Home Office","false","2018-04-11","<p>The Government recognises that crime against businesses causes damage and disruption to those businesses as well as having a negative impact on their customers and the wider community. However, we do not routinely collect data on the costs of different types of crimes to different types of businesses. We do have assessments of the costs of crime to the retail sector provided by our partners on the National Retail Crime Steering Group. For example, the British Retail Consortium has estimated that the direct financial cost of crime to the UK retail industry was £700 million in 2016-17. It estimated that the cost of customer theft was £503 million and the cost of fraud against the sector was £155 million.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-04-11T09:40:30.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862271/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862271/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862271/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-14","Business: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the cost of the different categories of crime to UK businesses.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","132690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862272","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-21","<p>To support the Government’s commitment to tackling loneliness, the Department has continued to embed addressing loneliness in a number of existing programmes across health and social care, including social prescribing, dementia friendly communities, mental health and carers, as well as identifying new opportunities to combat loneliness.</p><p> </p><p>We have seconded a Departmental official to the new central team leading the Government’s Loneliness Strategy, as well as identifying officials within the Department to coordinate our contribution to this important agenda. I am a member of the newly formed Ministerial Group on Loneliness.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-03-21T12:13:31.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862272/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862272/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862272/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Loneliness: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what resources his Department has allocated to tackle loneliness among older people in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","132691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862273","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-22","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-03-22T12:13:57.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862273/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862273/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862273/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Mental Illness: Alcoholic Drinks and Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what proportion of mental health service users also have co-morbid alcohol and drug dependence.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","132692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862274","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-22","<p>We are taking steps to increase the level of funding for mental health services in England. We have increased spending on mental health to a record £11.6 billion in 2016/17 and this is planned to rise to £11.86 billion in 2017/18. Detailed decisions about how much funding is spent on treatment or prevention are made locally, rather than centrally by the Department.</p><p> </p><p>The Mental Health Investment Standard (MHIS) requires all clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to increase funding for mental health by at least as much as the overall increase to their funding allocations. 85% of CCGs achieved the MHIS in 2016/17 and from 2018/19 all CCGs will be required to meet it.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-03-22T12:09:01.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862274/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862274/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862274/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what funding his Department has allocated for mental health (a) prevention and (b) treatment in the last year.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","132693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862275","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-22","<p>Information on bed levels is not held in the format requested.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-03-22T12:17:31.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862275/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862275/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862275/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many mental health beds have been closed since August 2013.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","132694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862276","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-22","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-03-22T15:55:38.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862276/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862276/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862276/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Self Harm: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many children and adolescents were admitted to hospital as a result of intentional self-harm in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","132695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862277","Department for Education","false","2018-03-26","<p>The department recently conducted the latest Employer Skills Survey, which provides robust assessments of skills shortages across the UK by region and by sector. The results of this survey will be published later in 2018 and will provide insight into different industries’ skill needs. Whilst we cannot identify General Aviation specifically through the survey, data relating to the aviation sector as a whole will be made available to the public. Findings from the previous Employer Skills Survey in 2015, which was run by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills, are available on <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ukces-employer-skills-survey-2015" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>. The department also holds responsibility for Working Futures, which provides labour market projections at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-labour-market-projections-2014-to-2024" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-labour-market-projections-2014-to-2024</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The department is also making our skills system more responsive to employer needs. As part of this, the department is forming Skills Advisory Panels, which aim to bring about a closer alignment between skills supply (from FE Colleges, training providers, apprenticeships, as well as centrally-held programmes) and local employer demand.<strong> <br> </strong></p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-03-26T16:59:53.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862277/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862277/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862277/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Aviation: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment his Department has made of the level of the skills shortage in the general aviation sector; and what steps his Department is taking to address that shortage.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","132696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862278","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-22","<p>The Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme (PPRS) operates by capping overall growth in expenditure on branded medicines within the scope of the scheme. Innovative medicines, defined as those containing a new active substance, have freedom of pricing at launch under the terms of the scheme. The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence assesses cost-effectiveness of the medicine and under the terms of the PPRS companies may offer discounts through a patient access scheme in order to secure a cost-effective price.</p><p> </p><p>In order for NHS England to manage affordability of any particular medicine a budget impact test may trigger a further commercial discussion with a company if the cost of the medicine may exceed £20 million in any of the first three years. Taken together these arrangements balance patient access to innovative cost-effective medicines with access to appropriate treatment for all patients, and secure best value for the taxpayer and a clear route to market for companies.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-22T17:16:12.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862278/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862278/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862278/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Drugs: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment his Department has made of whether further price reductions on innovative branded medicines are necessary given the majority of medicines are capped through the Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","132697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862279","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-21","<p>The £50 million funding over the next two years supports the priorities set out in the strategy, including investment to support a new wave of the Community-based English language, the Integration Areas programme and establishing a new Integration Innovation Fund to stimulate and test innovative approaches to promoting integration. We will announce more details of how the funding is allocated following the consultation which closes on 6 June 2018.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-03-21T17:26:21.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862279/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862279/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862279/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Community Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to his Department’s press release of 14 March 2017, how much of the £50 million of funding allocated to support the new Integrated Communities Strategy will be used to expand English for Speakers of Other Languages teaching.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","132698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862280","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-19","<p>Whilst trusts are in Special Measures for Quality, they will receive increased support and intensive oversight to help address specific failings. In respect of Kettering General Hospital NHS Foundation Trust, an NHS Improvement support package and Improvement Director have been put in place to help support the Trust’s improvement journey.</p><p> </p><p>Trusts in Special Measures for Quality, such as Kettering General Hospital NHS Foundation Trust, will exit if they have provided the Care Quality Commission with evidence of improvement in the quality of care delivered, if they are well-led, and if a solution can be found to sustain sufficient good quality care, in consultation with NHS Improvement.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-03-19T16:54:51.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862280/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862280/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862280/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Kettering Hospital: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what Kettering General Hospital needs to do to get out of special measures.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","132699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862281","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-19","<p>​We are aware of reports concerning the citizenship and eligibility of Klara Kabilova to sit as an MP in Kyrgyzstan. We have not made representations about this specific case but our Embassy in Bishkek has regular meetings with the Kyrgyz government at all levels and routinely discusses issues of mutual interest, including progress on democratisation, fundamental values and human rights.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-03-19T16:18:22.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862281/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862281/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862281/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-14","Klara Kabilova","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has made to the Government of Kyrgyzstan on the case of Klara Kabilova, the chairwoman of Kyrgyzstan's Central Election Commission.","false","Biography information for Wayne David","Caerphilly","Wayne David","132700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862282","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-19","<p>No funding allocated to programmes in the Department has been reallocated.</p><p>We secured additional flexibility to retain income at Autumn Budget to deliver our agenda, including EU exit.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-03-19T16:05:55.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862282/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862282/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how much funding allocated to programmes in his Department has been reallocated to programmes preparing for the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","132701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862283","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-19","<p>The Government has not made such an assessment.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-03-19T16:11:49.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862283/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862283/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862283/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-14","Public Health Funerals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of introducing (a) national minimum standards and (b) eligibility criteria to the administration of public health funerals.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","132702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862284","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-19","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that all families who lose a child are given the support they need. We already have the Social Fund Funeral Expenses Payment scheme to support eligible bereaved families in need of financial support, and I am leading a piece of work across government to:</p><ul><li>support Kevin Hollinrake’s Private Members’ Bill, to introduce Parental Bereavement (Leave and Pay) for parents who lose a child under the age of 18;</li><li>introduce a shorter application form for claims relating to children’s funerals from the Social Fund Funeral Expenses Payment scheme, making it easier for bereaved parents to apply for financial support; and</li><li>bring together information and support from across Government and more widely so it is easily accessible to bereaved parents.</li></ul>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-03-19T16:14:33.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862284/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862284/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862284/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-14","Funerals: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the Government has plans to introduce a children's funeral fund.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","132703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862285","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-20","<p>The Social Fund Funeral Expenses Payments continue to meet the necessary costs of a cremation or burial for eligible claimants. Average payments have increased year-on-year to meet these necessary costs. We have had to make difficult choices about welfare spending and it has not been possible to increase the £700 maximum for other costs. However we have made interest-free Social Fund Budgeting Loans available for funeral costs in addition to Funeral Expenses Payments.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016/17, approximately 27,000 Funeral Expenses Payments were paid worth around £38.6 million. The average payment made has increased in value in the past ten years by about 28 per cent – from £1,117 in 2006/07 to £1,427 in 2016/17 – as the necessary costs have increased.</p><p> </p><p>We need to ensure that we have a system that is both fair for tax payers, while assisting the most vulnerable with funeral expenses. The Funeral Expenses Payments scheme continues to make a significant contribution towards the cost of a simple funeral for claimants on certain income based benefits or tax credits.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-20T15:45:00.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862285/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862285/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-14","Funeral Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of the maximum level of funeral expenses payments, in relation to recent trends in funeral costs.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","132704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862286","Department for Education","false","2018-03-20","<p>Pay spine points for teachers were discontinued in 2013 and replaced by pay ranges. A teacher can be paid any salary within their range, the amount paid being at the discretion of the employing school. An academy may elect not to use the standard pay ranges but may instead pay teachers using their own range.</p><p> </p><p>The number of teachers in state funded schools paid on each pay range, as at November 2016, is shown in the attached table.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","132706","2018-03-20T17:57:30.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862286/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862286/answer","132705 132706 attachment.docx","132705 132706 attachment.docx","132705 132706 attachment","132705 132706 attachment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862286/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862286/answer/previousversion/48376","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Teachers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information his Department holds on the number of teachers on each point of the main pay range.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","132705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862287","Department for Education","false","2018-03-20","<p>Pay spine points for teachers were discontinued in 2013 and replaced by pay ranges. A teacher can be paid any salary within their range, the amount paid being at the discretion of the employing school. An academy may elect not to use the standard pay ranges but may instead pay teachers using their own range.</p><p> </p><p>The number of teachers in state funded schools paid on each pay range, as at November 2016, is shown in the attached table.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","132705","2018-03-20T17:57:31.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862287/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862287/answer","132705 132706 attachment.docx","132705 132706 attachment.docx","132705 132706 attachment","132705 132706 attachment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862287/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862287/answer/previousversion/48394","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Teachers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information his Department holds on the number of teachers on each point of the upper pay range.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","132706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862288","Treasury","false","2018-03-19","<p>Early education is a devolved matter for a restored Northern Ireland Executive. We have delivered a successful 30 hours policy for working parents in England, and will provide advice to the Northern Ireland parties based on our experience of developing and administering policies in England.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-03-19T17:39:10.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862288/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862288/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-14","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the oral contribution from the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions of 13 March 2018, Official Report, column 768, on what date he plans to provide further details of the roll out of childcare support in Northern Ireland similar to 30 hours of funded childcare in England.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","132707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862289","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-20","<p>The Criminal Cases Review Commissioner (CCRC) have referred two cases more than once since 1997.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-03-20T13:09:35.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862289/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862289/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-14","Criminal Cases Review Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many cases have been referred to the Court of Appeal by the Criminal Cases Review Commission more than once since 1997.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","132708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862290","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-22","<p>Government recognises the importance of the creative industries and directly supports them in a number of ways, including tax credits, regional development programmes and other funding programmes. Future spending will be determined through normal budgetary processes.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-03-22T15:24:04.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862290/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862290/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-03-14","Arts: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what plans his Department has to increase funding from the public purse to the creative industries.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","132709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862291","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-22","<p>The UK is a Party to the 1992 European Convention on Cinematographic Co-production. This is not affected by the UK’s departure from the European Union.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-03-22T15:24:45.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862291/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862291/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-03-14","European Convention On Cinematographic Co-production","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether his Department is taking steps to ensure that the European Convention on Cinematographic Co-Production applies to the UK after it leaves the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","132710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862292","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-22","<p>Government is continuing to work closely with stakeholders from across the creative industries to fully understand the potential impacts and opportunities of the UK’s exit from the European Union, which includes the ability of the UK entertainment sector to work and tour across Europe.</p><p> </p><p>We are working closely with the Home Office, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) and the Department for Exiting the European Union (DExEU) to ensure that they are well informed of the issues for the creative industries.</p><p> </p><p>We want to continue to build on the success of the UK entertainment industry and are committed to supporting industry performance across the world.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-03-22T15:26:50.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862292/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862292/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-03-14","Entertainers: Free Movement of People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the loss of freedom of movement on the UK entertainment sector.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","132711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862293","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-22","<p>In her Mansion House speech the Prime Minister made clear that the UK is committed to continuing cultural and educational participation with the EU. This would enable the UK to participate in key programmes alongside our EU partners to promote our shared values and enhance our intellectual strength in the world.</p><p> </p><p>We have agreed a fair financial settlement with the EU enabling us to move to the next stage of negotiations, and will continue to benefit from EU programmes under this budget plan. Organisations that receive European funding can continue to bid for and receive funding until the end of their projects.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-03-22T15:28:38.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862293/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862293/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-03-14","Arts: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether his Department has plans to replicate Creative Europe funding for UK creative industries after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","132712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862294","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-22","<p>The Department has had no discussions on reducing the cost of Savitex. The decision to prescribe and fund a licensed treatment on the National Health Service is taken by the relevant clinician and commissioner (such as NHS England or individual clinical commissioning groups) based on the individual needs of the patient.</p><p> </p><p>When the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) published its guideline on the treatment of adults with multiple sclerosis (MS) in 2014, it recommended that Sativex should not be offered as an option to treat spasticity in people with MS because it is not a cost effective treatment. NICE is responsible for determining whether its guidance should be updated following the publication of any significant new evidence.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-22T17:28:38.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862294/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862294/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Nabiximols","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 12 March 2018 to Question 130778 on Nabiximols, what progress his Department has made on reducing the cost of the drug Sativex.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","132713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862295","Department for Education","false","2018-03-20","<p>I held a meeting on 12 March with interested MPs and representatives from a leading charity within the field, and have scheduled another meeting with that charity and further interested MPs on 20 March. During frequent visits to schools I engage with teachers and students and discuss a range of topics including sign language.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has introduced a number of recent changes to GCSEs, AS and A levels in England that will affect schools in the coming years. We know that extensive changes need time to settle in, and that school leaders will want stability to bring in the new qualifications. There are no plans to introduce new GCSEs, AS or A levels in this Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>Schools are free to teach British Sign Language and there are existing qualifications available which schools can enter pupils into at any point of their school career. These include a Level 1 award, Level 2, 3 and 4 certificates and a Level 6 NVQ certificate. British Sign Language is also now an alternative to a Level 1 and Level 2 qualification in English when studying an apprenticeship, where British Sign Language is the apprentice’s primary language. This enables those who use British Sign Language to complete their apprenticeship without having to achieve another English qualification, such as GCSE or Functional Skills.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-03-20T18:08:36.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862295/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862295/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862295/answer/previousversion/48390","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Sign Language: GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent discussions he has held with (a) examination boards, (b) teachers, (c) students and (d) other stakeholders on the creation of a GCSE in British Sign Language; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","132714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862296","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-19","<p>The use of arts and culture was not specifically included in the consultation for the recent Green Paper on children and young people’s mental health. The full list of consultation questions were published alongside the Green Paper itself and are available on the Department website.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-03-19T11:32:29.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862296/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862296/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Mental Health: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether the use of (a) the arts and (b) culture was included in the consultation on the Green Paper on Transforming children and young people's mental health.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","132715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862297","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-19","<p>Health in All Policies (HiAP) is a collaborative approach to improving the health of all people by incorporating health considerations into decision making across sectors, policy and service areas, and addressing the wider determinants of health.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England worked with the Association of Directors of Public Health and the Local Government Association to develop masterclasses to understand how to support Directors of Public Health and local government to adopt health and health equity in all policies at a local level. The HiAP approach has been adopted in various forms by Swindon, Medway, Bristol and Blackburn Councils.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-19T14:32:25.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862297/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862297/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862297/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Public Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department has taken to implement Public Health England's Health in all policies, published in October 2016.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","132716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862298","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-19","<p>An assessment has not been made of the cost of bidding for funds from the Transforming Cities Fund, but the Government is mindful of the cost to Local Authorities of bidding for local transport funding. That is why the bidding process for the Transforming Cities Fund has been designed to be light-touch, and eligibility has been limited to the largest English cities to maximise cost-effectiveness for bidders while still delivering value for money for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>City regions have been initially encouraged to provide light-touch expressions of interest through a Call for Proposals, and the Department will work closely with shortlisted city regions to develop the strongest possible proposals.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-03-19T14:27:57.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862298/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862298/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862298/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-14","Transforming Cities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the cost of bidding for funds from the City Transformation Fund.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","132717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862299","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-19","<p>Due to commercial confidentiality, we do not comment on the financial position of individual franchises.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-03-19T14:33:17.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862299/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862299/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862299/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-14","East Anglia Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether Greater Anglia rail franchise is meeting its financial performance targets; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","132718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862300","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-19","<p>Due to commercial confidentiality, we do not comment on the financial position of individual franchises. We work closely with all our franchisees throughout their contracts and monitor their progress against their contractual commitments. We expect all operators and their guarantors to continue to fulfil their financial and contractual commitments.</p><p> </p><p>The Department awarded this franchise after a robust competition process and the owning group has provided a substantial parent company support as a guarantee.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-03-19T14:38:23.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862300/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862300/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-14","East Anglia Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the premium payments of £3.8 billion on the Greater Anglia rail franchise will be paid in full.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","132719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862301","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-19","<p>We work closely with all our franchisees throughout their contracts and monitor their progress against their contractual commitments. We expect all operators and their guarantors to continue to fulfil their financial and contractual commitments.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-03-19T14:30:20.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862301/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862301/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-14","East Anglia Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of whether the Greater Anglia rail franchise contract will be fulfilled.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","132720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862302","Department for Education","false","2018-03-19","<p>We know that many people unable to give birth, such as those with Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser syndrome, look to alternatives such as adoption and surrogacy.</p><p> </p><p>The process of adopting a child in England is free for all eligible adopters whether they approach a local authority or a voluntary adoption agency. Local authorities have the power to make discretionary financial payments to adopters for the purpose of supporting the placement of the adoptive child with them or the continuation of adoption arrangements after an adoption order is made. In addition, local authorities are required to assess the need for post-adoption support when requested by adoptive parents or children.</p><p> </p><p>The government has invested significantly in adoption support through the Adoption Support Fund. Since its launch in May 2015, more than £66 million has been provided for thousands of families to access therapeutic support.</p><p> </p><p>Decisions about local NHS services, including assisted conception and fertility treatment, are the responsibility of local Clinical Commissioning Groups and will take into account the overall needs of the local population. Individual cases where patients suffer from conditions such as Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser syndrome may be given exceptional consideration.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-03-19T17:41:45.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862302/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862302/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Adoption and Surrogate Motherhood: MRKH Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether his Department is taking steps to assist people with Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser syndrome with the financial costs of (a) adoption and (b) surrogacy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","132721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862303","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-19","<p>The Government’s Consultation Principles replaced the previous Code of Practice in July 2012. The latest version dated 14 January 2016 requires that “Consultations should last for a proportionate amount of time”. In this case, the proposals were the subject of informal discussion between the UK motor industry and the department’s technical experts prior to the consultation launch.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-03-19T15:00:27.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862303/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862303/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-14","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of Transport, for what reasons his Department's consultation entitled Road Vehicles Improving Air quality and Safety has run for a period of four weeks rather than the 12 weeks recommended in the Code of Practice on Consultation.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","132722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862304","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-04-03","<p>The Secretary of State for Northern Ireland set out in a Written Ministerial statement about Northern Ireland Finances on 8 March resource and capital allocations for Northern Ireland Departments for the financial year 2018/19. On 20 March, the Secretary of State brought forward the Northern Ireland Budget (Anticipation and Adjustments) Bill which would provide a “Vote on Account” for the Northern Ireland Administration to undertake expenditure in the early months of 2018/19 for day to day spending. This vote on account is part of the normal estimates process and these allocations will need to be placed on a legal footing later in the year. We hope a restored Executive will be in place to take this through the Northern Ireland Assembly. The Secretary of State does not have the power to take forward a budget through an Order-in-Council.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-04-03T12:27:39.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862304/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862304/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-03-14","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to her oral contribution of 12 March 2018, Official Report, columns 641 to 642, whether she plans to set the budget for Northern Ireland through an Order-in-Council; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","132723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862305","Home Office","false","2018-03-21","<p>We have plans to publish statistics about applications made by survivors and relatives of victims and survivors in due course, once the data has been properly assured.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-21T16:13:14.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862305/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862305/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-14","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to publish statistics on applications by survivors and relatives of victims and survivors under the Grenfell Tower relatives policy.","false","Biography information for Emma Dent Coad","Kensington","Emma Dent Coad","132724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862306","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-03-19","<p>As the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland told the House in her statement on 12 March 2018, she will seek to introduce legislation to take a power to vary MLA pay. The UK Government would welcome representations from the Northern Ireland political parties before and during that process, to inform the exercise of that power, and will publish in full any such representations.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","132739","2018-03-19T13:02:47.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862306/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862306/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862306/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-03-14","Northern Ireland Assembly: Members","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to her oral contribution of 12 March 2018, Official Report, column 642, if she will set out the timescale to receive full and final representations from the Northern Ireland political parties before she makes a final decision on reducing the salaries of Members of the Legislative Assembly; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","132725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862307","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-21","<p>The ESA65B letter is issued to GPs in every case where an Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) claimant has been found ‘fit for work’. This process was built into the IT system as part of the introduction of ESA in October 2008.</p><p> </p><p>Following a Ministerial requirement by the Cabinet Secretary, which was endorsed by the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, the content of the ESA65B letter has been improved in order to explain to GPs the type of support customers can expect to receive from their local Jobcentre, and to ask GPs to encourage customers in their efforts to return to work. As part of this work officials engaged with the British Medical Association and the Royal College of General Practitioners to ensure that the revised wording was fit for purpose.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold information on the number of ESA65B letters sent to GPs.</p><p> </p><p>I will place a copy of the ESA65B in the House Library.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","132727 ; 132729","2018-03-21T13:49:45.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862307/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862307/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862307/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-14","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 14 February 2018 to Question 127010, on employment and support allowance, how many ESA65B letters her Department has sent to doctors.","false","Biography information for Emma Dent Coad","Kensington","Emma Dent Coad","132726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862308","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-21","<p>The ESA65B letter is issued to GPs in every case where an Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) claimant has been found ‘fit for work’. This process was built into the IT system as part of the introduction of ESA in October 2008.</p><p> </p><p>Following a Ministerial requirement by the Cabinet Secretary, which was endorsed by the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, the content of the ESA65B letter has been improved in order to explain to GPs the type of support customers can expect to receive from their local Jobcentre, and to ask GPs to encourage customers in their efforts to return to work. As part of this work officials engaged with the British Medical Association and the Royal College of General Practitioners to ensure that the revised wording was fit for purpose.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold information on the number of ESA65B letters sent to GPs.</p><p> </p><p>I will place a copy of the ESA65B in the House Library.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","132726 ; 132729","2018-03-21T13:49:45.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862308/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862308/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862308/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-14","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 14 February 2018 to Question 127010, on employment and support allowance, when her Department started sending ESA65B letters to GPs; and whether that policy was authorised by Ministers.","false","Biography information for Emma Dent Coad","Kensington","Emma Dent Coad","132727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862309","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-20","<p>This Government has committed to a comprehensive and ambitious set of city deals in Northern Ireland. Belfast City Region are developing a set of proposals which they intend to submit to Government as the basis for a city deal discussion, and I look forward to seeing them.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-03-20T17:07:51.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862309/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862309/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","City Deals: Belfast","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of progress on the Belfast City Deal; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","132728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862310","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-21","<p>The ESA65B letter is issued to GPs in every case where an Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) claimant has been found ‘fit for work’. This process was built into the IT system as part of the introduction of ESA in October 2008.</p><p> </p><p>Following a Ministerial requirement by the Cabinet Secretary, which was endorsed by the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, the content of the ESA65B letter has been improved in order to explain to GPs the type of support customers can expect to receive from their local Jobcentre, and to ask GPs to encourage customers in their efforts to return to work. As part of this work officials engaged with the British Medical Association and the Royal College of General Practitioners to ensure that the revised wording was fit for purpose.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold information on the number of ESA65B letters sent to GPs.</p><p> </p><p>I will place a copy of the ESA65B in the House Library.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","132726 ; 132727","2018-03-21T13:49:45.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862310/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862310/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-14","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 14 February 2018 to Question 127010, on employment and support allowance, if she will place a copy of the ESA65B letter that her Department sends to GPs in the Library.","false","Biography information for Emma Dent Coad","Kensington","Emma Dent Coad","132729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862311","Treasury","false","2018-03-20","<p>HMRC hold regular meetings with childcare voucher providers, and will be holding another forum shortly. Employers for Childcare will be invited to attend.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-03-20T15:50:57.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862311/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862311/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-14","Child Care Vouchers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will meet representatives of Employers for Childcare to discuss its concerns about the closure of the childcare voucher scheme  to new entrants after the six-month extension; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","132730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862312","Leader of the House","false","2018-03-19","<p>The issue of representative money is primarily a matter for the House. No discussions have taken place on this issue.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2018-03-19T11:02:15.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862312/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862312/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2018-03-14","Sinn Fein: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, with which political parties she has discussed reducing the amount of representative money given to Sinn Fein; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","132731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862313","Department for Education","false","2018-04-04","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost. The Department has published some statistics for Key Stage 2 attainment for individual parliamentary constituencies since 2011/2[1]. Please be aware that the headline measures used across the years have changed and that comparison between years is not advised.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not publish constituency level attainment data for Key Stage 1.</p><p> </p><p>[1] For 2011/12 – 2013/14 the information is located here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/national-curriculum-assessments-at-key-stage-2-2014-revised" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/national-curriculum-assessments-at-key-stage-2-2014-revised</a> - open the ‘parliamentary constituency tables’, you can change year in the top right. This table provides the percentage achieving level 4 or above in each subject.</p><p>For 2014/15, the information is located here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/national-curriculum-assessments-at-key-stage-2-2015-revised" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/national-curriculum-assessments-at-key-stage-2-2015-revised</a> - open the ‘additional tables’ and then tab ‘Table B3’. This table provides the percentage achieving level 4 or above in each subject.</p><p>For 2015/16, the information is located here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/national-curriculum-assessments-key-stage-2-2016-revised" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/national-curriculum-assessments-key-stage-2-2016-revised</a> - open the ‘additional tables’ and then tab ‘Table A5’. This table provides the percentage achieving the epected standard in each subject.</p><p>For 2016/17 the information is located here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/national-curriculum-assessments-key-stage-2-2017-revised" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/national-curriculum-assessments-key-stage-2-2017-revised</a> - open the ‘additional tables’ and then tab ‘Table A5’, this table provides the progress score of pupils in each subject, in line with the updated headline measures for key stage 2 attainment.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-04-04T15:54:10.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862313/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862313/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Reading: Witham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of pupils in Witham constituency (a) attained and (b) exceeded the minimum standard for reading at (i) key stage 1 and (ii) key stage 2 in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","132732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862314","Department for Education","false","2018-03-22","<p>Being able to read is vital for children’s future success. Thanks to the Government reforms and the hard work of teachers across the country, 154,000 more six year olds are on track to become fluent readers, and international evidence has shown that our nine year olds have achieved their highest ever scores in reading. In 2017, 82% of children in Essex passed the phonics screening check, slightly above the national average. Schools in Essex are benefitting from funding to support school improvement in reading outcomes for boys in primary and secondary schools, and to improve the teaching of phonics in primary schools.</p><p>The Department wants to build on these successes by supporting teachers to further raise standards for all children. We have announced that we will set up a new Centre of Excellence for Literacy Teaching and a national network of 35 English Hubs across the country. The exact locations of hubs will be decided in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-03-22T12:42:42.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862314/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862314/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Literacy: Essex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department is taking to raise standards of literacy at schools in Essex.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","132733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862315","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-22","<p>Guidance on the management of foreign national offenders subject to MAPPA is contained in the MAPPA Guidance available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/multi-agency-public-protection-arrangements-mappa--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/multi-agency-public-protection-arrangements-mappa--2</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The number of foreign national offenders who are subject to multi-agency public protection arrangements in each police area could only be obtained at disproportionate cost. This is because the information is held locally by individual lead agencies within the 42 MAPPA areas and is not collated centrally.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-03-22T16:41:08.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862315/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862315/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-14","Offenders: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to monitor foreign national offenders who are subject to multi-agency public protection arrangements; and if he will set out the number of foreign national offenders who are subject to multi-agency public protection arrangements in each police area.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","132734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862316","Home Office","false","2018-03-21","<p>The Home Office does not disclose country specific information regarding deportation of foreign national offenders as its disclosure could prejudice relations between the UK and foreign governments.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-21T16:19:02.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862316/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862316/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-14","Offenders: Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many foreign national offenders were deported to each country in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","132735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862317","Home Office","false","2018-03-22","<p>Providing the information requested would require a manual check of individual records which could only be done at disproportionate cost.</p><p>Anyone subject to a deportation order is placed on a watchlist and banned from re-entering the UK. Should a foreign national offender wish to return then they will have to apply for their deportation order to be revoked.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-22T15:16:27.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862317/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862317/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-14","Offenders: Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people who had been deported from the UK as a result of (a) a criminal prosecution and (b) committing terrorism-related offences subsequently returned to the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","132736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862318","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-22","<p>Any foreign national who comes to our country and abuses our hospitality by breaking the law should be in no doubt of our determination to deport them. More than 40,000 Foreign National Offenders have been removed from the UK since 2010, and in the last financial year a record number of over 6,300 were removed.</p><p>The Ministry of Justice, HMPPS, and HMCTS do not hold the information requested in the PQ. Home Office have confirmed that as ‘Nationality’ is not a mandatory field on the Police National Computer (PNC) the Home Office cannot provide the information requested in the PQ.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-03-22T17:34:35.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862318/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862318/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-14","Offenders: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many foreign national offenders have been convicted of multiple offences in the UK.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","132737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862319","Home Office","false","2018-03-21","<p>The Home Office routinely publish quarterly figures on the average length of time to deport a foreign national offender. Figures for the latest quarter can be found by accessing the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-enforcement-data-february-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-enforcement-data-february-2018</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-21T16:41:18.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862319/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862319/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-14","Offenders: Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how long it takes on average to deport a foreign national offender between their release from custody and their departure from the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","132738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862320","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-03-19","<p>As the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland told the House in her statement on 12 March 2018, she will seek to introduce legislation to take a power to vary MLA pay. The UK Government would welcome representations from the Northern Ireland political parties before and during that process, to inform the exercise of that power, and will publish in full any such representations.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","132725","2018-03-19T13:02:47.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862320/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862320/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-03-14","Northern Ireland Assembly: Members","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to her oral contribution of 12 March 2018, Official Report, column 642, if she will publish the full and final representations from the Northern Ireland political parties about reducing the salaries of Members of the Legislative Assembly; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","132739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862321","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-22","<p>I have offered to meet with the family of Asa Hutchinson as Minister responsible for relations with the Middle East and North Africa and did so on 21 March 2018.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-03-22T16:19:32.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862321/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862321/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862321/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-14","Asa Hutchinson","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 26 February 2018 to Question 129007, if he will meet with the family of Asa Hutchinson.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","132740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862322","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-22","<p>Planning applications can be submitted to relevant local authorities at any time. The decision by a local authority must be taken in accordance with the development plan unless there are material considerations that indicate otherwise.</p><p>The Secretary of State would not routinely play a role in the decision making of a local authority, but does have the power to call-in an application for his own decision. This is subject to the criteria that the application conflicts with the national policy in important matters, or is nationally significant.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-03-22T11:45:48.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862322/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862322/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Garden Communities: North Essex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, on what date will planning applications be accepted for the proposed North Essex Garden Communities; and what role will his Department play in the process.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","132741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862323","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-22","<p>Across England we are already supporting twenty-four locally-led garden cities, towns and villages to be exemplars of quality, design and best practice. All told, they have the potential to deliver up to 220,000 homes across England. This includes the North Essex Garden Communities.</p><p>To date, we have provided capacity funding totalling £2.023 million to North Essex Garden Communities via our Garden Towns and Villages programme. This will enable dedicated staff to be employed and sustainable housing growth and infrastructure to be planned for, raising the bar on quality and design and leaving a legacy for future generations to be proud of.</p><p>It is for the local authorities to ensure that funding received is spent in line with any grant conditions. Homes England continue to provide delivery expertise to local areas, ensuring that capacity funding is best able to unlock delivery of homes.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-03-22T11:36:15.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862323/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862323/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862323/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Garden Communities: North Essex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what funds his Department has provided for the North Essex Garden Communities scheme; and what limits his Department has placed on the expenditure of those funds.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","132742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862324","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-22","<p>Across England we are already supporting twenty-four locally-led garden cities, towns and villages to be exemplars of quality, design and best practice. All told, they have the potential to deliver up to 220,000 homes across England.</p><p>Autumn Budget 2017 announced that we will extend this support to deliver five new garden towns that will seek to bring together public and private capital. This recognises the importance of private sector investment to deliver new garden settlements.</p><p>To help achieve this ambition, we are introducing legislation to enable locally accountable New Town Development Corporations to be created as a key instrument of delivery. We expect such operational independence to be attractive to private sector investment to get on with the job of delivering any new garden settlement.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-03-22T11:45:20.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862324/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862324/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862324/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Garden Communities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to encourage and support private sector investment in proposed garden settlements.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","132743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862325","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-19","<p>Under Local Government Act 2003, local authorities have the freedom to borrow and invest, without government consent, provided that their borrowing is affordable. As part of this ‘prudential’ framework, every local authority is required to set its own borrowing limit, which must be approved by full Council or the equivalent at least annually. The Government has backstop powers to set national borrowing limits at times of economic crisis, which would override the normal prudential freedoms. These powers have never been used.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-03-19T16:56:04.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862325/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862325/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862325/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Garden Communities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what the criteria for and restrictions on borrowing for local authorities are in relation to garden settlement proposals.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","132744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862326","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-03-20","<p>The Secretary of State’s future travel programme takes into account a range of high priority issues. The Secretary of State has been to the border, prior to his appointment to his current role, and is very much apprised of the sensitivities and importance of this critical issue.</p><p> </p><p>He previously visited Northern Ireland in September 2016 meeting with the then Northern Ireland Executive and stakeholders. Parliamentary Under Secretary of State, Robin Walker MP, visited Northern Ireland with former Northern Ireland Office Minister Chloe Smith in September 2017, visiting the border and meeting with Re-Gen waste and InterTradeIreland.</p><p> </p><p>Northern Ireland Office Ministers have also conducted an extensive programme of engagement in Northern Ireland on EU exit with a wide range of stakeholders. The Secretary of State for Northern Ireland visited the border earlier this month.</p>","Fareham","Suella Fernandes",,"2018-03-20T16:06:26.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862326/answer","Biography information for Suella Braverman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862326/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-03-14","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what plans the Secretary of State has to visit the border between the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Hugh Gaffney","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Hugh Gaffney","132745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862327","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-19","<p>The Secretary of State had regard to all the relevant information available to him when considering the proposal from Dorset councils including, as I referenced in my answer to Question UIN 131575 on 12 March 2018, the findings of the open questionnaire and the household survey, as well as any comments and representations relating to the questionnaire and survey.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-03-19T16:01:12.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862327/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862327/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Local Government: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 12 March 2018 to Question 131575, on Local Government: Dorset, what assessment he has made of the finding in paragraph 1.42 of the Final Report of Opinion Research Services on Researching your councils' consultation that the household survey is a better guide than the open questionnaire to the balance of public opinion across Christchurch.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Sir Christopher Chope","132746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862328","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-19","<p>I have not met with officials from Code Blue but I have been briefed by DFID officials on Code Blue’s concerns about the allegations of sexual harassment at UNAIDS. My officials met with Code Blue on 28 February to discuss this issue and informed them of the measures the UK is taking to raise safeguarding standards with all our partners, including UNAIDS, and that tackling harassment will be a priority during our Chairmanship of the Programme and Coordinating Board.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2018-03-19T17:02:22.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862328/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862328/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862328/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-14","UNAIDS: Sexual Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether she has met the campaign group Code Blue to discuss concerns about sexual harassment at UNAIDs; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","132747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862329","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-19","<p>An extensive public consultation was undertaken by Opinion Research Services on behalf of all nine Dorset councils between 30 August 2016 and 25 October 2016, including an open consultation questionnaire, a representative household survey based upon 20,000 randomly selected households, a survey of all parish and town councils, 15 workshops, nine in depth interviews and written submissions. Full details of this are available at: <a href="http://www.futuredorset.co.uk/" target="_blank">www.futuredorset.co.uk</a></p><p>Following the Secretary of State’s announcement on 7 November 2017, further representations were invited until 8 January 2018. Over 200 representations were received in this period, all of which were taken into account by the Secretary of State before making his decision, announced on 26 February 2018.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-03-19T16:05:23.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862329/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862329/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862329/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Local Government: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Written Statement of 7 November 2017, Local Government Improvement, HCWS 232, what public consultation preceded that policy announcement; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Sir Christopher Chope","132748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862330","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-19","<p>I have been firm in my demand that agencies show leadership and take action alongside the UK to improve reporting mechanisms for sexual exploitation and abuse, and have requested information on the measures that they have in place and assurance that these are being effectively implemented. I will assess the evidence that they provide to determine what action needs to be taken.</p><p> </p><p>DFID is leading and convening a group of likeminded donors to develop a strong, consistent approach to sexual harassment, intimidation and sexual exploitation and abuse, across the development and humanitarian sectors. This includes reviewing and shaping UNAIDS proposal for an independent, external panel to develop concrete recommendations to strengthen zero tolerance policies, including sexual harassment and abuse of power.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2018-03-19T17:00:28.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862330/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862330/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862330/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-14","UNAIDS: Sexual Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make an assessment of the merits of a system for reporting sexual harassment which is independent of senior management at UNAIDs; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","132749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862331","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-19","<p>Redundancy policies are a matter for individual councils having regard to the contracts of employment into which they have entered. The Dorset councils have informally indicated their expectation that there would be very few cases where redundancy payments would exceed £95,000, and even in such cases any excess over £95,000 would be minimal.</p><p>The Government is supportive of the principle of a cap of £95,000. In 2016 the Government legislated to cap exit payments across the public sector to a maximum of £95,000. A consultation on proposed implementation arrangements will be forthcoming in 2018.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-03-19T16:00:37.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862331/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862331/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862331/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Local Government: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what response his Department received to its suggestion that councils in Dorset should apply a voluntary cap of £95,000 to any exit payments arising from local government reorganisation.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Sir Christopher Chope","132750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862893","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-27","<p>The UK government has read the report by the International Rescue Committee (IRC) and by the UNHCR. We agree with the findings of the reports however, the needs have since increased significantly and the humanitarian crisis is now the biggest in Africa. 13.1 million people now require humanitarian assistance. 4.5 million people are internally displaced – the highest number in Africa. Over 680,000 refugees from the DRC are now in over 14 other countries in Africa.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-03-27T16:00:57.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862893/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862893/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-14","Democratic Republic of Congo: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the (1) the findings of the report by the International Rescue Committee A Silent Crisis in Congo: The Bantu and the Twa in Tanganyika that between July 2016 and March 2017 more than 400 villages in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) have been destroyed, and (2) the findings of the report by UNHCR that in 2017 (a) 1.7 million people across the DRC were forced to flee their homes, (b) 3.9 million remain internally displaced, and (c) more than 600,000 refugees from the DRC are spread over 11 African countries.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862894","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-22","<p>UK Bilateral aid over the next 5 years (2017-2022) will support 350,000 children under the age of five with vital nutrition and humanitarian assistance.</p><p>In December last year, the former Minister for Africa, Rory Stewart announced additional support which includes a focus on critical lifesaving nutrition interventions. Our wider programming also addresses and contributes to tackling the causes of malnutrition. For example our water and sanitation programme provided over 2 million people with a source of clean drinking water between June 2013 and July 2017 and through our health programme we have reached over 760,000 people with home visits and supplements for pregnant women.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to review the needs and the capacity to respond to critical humanitarian needs in the DRC. We are actively lobbying for other member states to step up their support. The international donor conference on the 13<sup>th</sup> April will provide a further opportunity to raise awareness of the critical situation in the DRC and for the government of the DRC (GoDRC) to demonstrate that they will also work to address the causes and consequence of this humanitarian crisis.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-03-22T15:40:20.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862894/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862894/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-14","Democratic Republic of Congo: Humanitarian Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how they intend to respond to the United Nations’ briefing at Geneva this week which stated that over two million children in the Democratic Republic of the Congo are at risk of starvation if they do not receive urgent humanitarian assistance.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862895","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-27","<p>Strengthening governance, and tackling crime and corruption, is fundamental to poverty reduction overseas and promotes our national security at home. UK aid focuses on tackling poverty and building stability in developing countries, which includes combatting corruption and helping developing countries to build robust institutions and tax systems so they can stand on their own two feet. Where a government fails to demonstrate long-term commitment to the values we expect of them, including good governance and tackling corruption, we do not fund that government directly but channel our support in other ways, for example, through non-governmental or multilateral organisations, to ensure it reaches the people who need it most.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-03-27T16:05:37.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862895/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862895/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-14","Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to act on the proposal made by David Cameron, in his role as chairman of the Commission on State Fragility, Growth and Development, that nations who fail to meet "basic norms of governance", and whose leaders are corrupt, should not continue to be recipients of UK aid.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862896","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-27","<p>DFID is not aware of the specific countries David Cameron was citing, nor is there a single comprehensive measure of wealth from which to derive those countries from. However, information on how much official development assistance the UK provides to individual developing countries is published in Statistics on International Development, which is available with this link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistics-on-international-development-2017" target="_blank">Statistics on International Development 2017 - GOV.UK</a></p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-03-27T16:04:37.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862896/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862896/answer","SID-2017b.pdf","SID-2017b.pdf","Statistics on International Development 2017","Statistics on International Development 2017","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862896/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-14","Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which of the countries cited by David Cameron, in his role as chairman of the Commission on State Fragility, Growth and Development, as "poorer than they were 40 years ago despite the aid that has been delivered there" have been recipients of UK aid; and how much aid has been provided to each of those countries over the last 30 years.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862897","Department for Education","false","2018-04-20","<p>The information requested in not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The department’s modelling estimates the difference in those eligible and claiming under the new government regulations compared to those eligible and claiming under the previous benefits system.</p><p> </p><p>From the modelling, we estimate that by 2022, around 50,000 more children will benefit from free school meals compared to the previous benefits system.</p><p> </p><p>The government is committed to reviewing the level of the threshold in order to ensure that the children in need of free school meals the most will continue to receive.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","HL6346","2018-04-20T13:52:58.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862897/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862897/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Free School Meals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many pupils would have been entitled to free school meals in 2022 under the previous system of benefits-based eligibility; and how many pupils will be entitled under the system of eligibility based on receipt of Universal Credit.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL6345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862898","Department for Education","false","2018-04-20","<p>The information requested in not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The department’s modelling estimates the difference in those eligible and claiming under the new government regulations compared to those eligible and claiming under the previous benefits system.</p><p> </p><p>From the modelling, we estimate that by 2022, around 50,000 more children will benefit from free school meals compared to the previous benefits system.</p><p> </p><p>The government is committed to reviewing the level of the threshold in order to ensure that the children in need of free school meals the most will continue to receive.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","HL6345","2018-04-20T13:52:58.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862898/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862898/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Free School Meals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many pupils will be entitled to free school meals for each year from 2022 to 2030.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL6346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862899","Department for Education","false","2018-04-20","<p>The department estimates that by 2022, around 50,000 more children will benefit from a free school meal compared to the previous benefits system.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2018-04-20T13:50:49.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862899/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862899/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Free School Meals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many children previously ineligible for free school meals will now become eligible as a result of the adoption of the new earnings threshold of £7,400 excluding benefits.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL6347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862900","Department for Education","false","2018-04-20","<p>Pupils eligible for free school meals will retain eligibility when transferring from primary to secondary school under the new system.</p><p> </p><p>During the period of Universal Credit (UC) rollout, those who claim free school meals will retain their eligibility even if their income rises above £7,400, because of the protections the government has put in place. At the end of UC rollout, those children who were protected – if they are still in school – will continue to be protected until the end of their phase of education (such as primary or secondary school).</p><p> </p><p>The department has not produced forecasts of the number of children receiving free school meals, protected or otherwise, that transition between primary and secondary school.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2018-04-20T13:51:09.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862900/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862900/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Free School Meals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether pupils transferring from primary school to secondary school who are currently entitled to free school meals will carry with them a continuing entitlement under the new arrangements; and if that entitlement ceases, how many children will be affected in each year to 2027.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL6348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862901","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-21","<p>This information is not held centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Significant information is held on individual court files but is not reported to the MoJ due to its size and complexity. This information would need to be individually inspected to see whether or not remand pending a psychiatric report had taken place in each case.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2018-03-21T17:05:12.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862901/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862901/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-14","Prisoners on Remand: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many women were remanded in custody whilst a psychiatric report was prepared for the court in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL6349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862902","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-27","<p>NHS Digital publishes information on workforce statistics and the latest data shows that the number of full time equivalent (FTE) child and adolescent psychiatrists in Greater Manchester increased by 13 between September 2015 and September 2017.</p><p>The following table shows the number of FTE child and adolescent psychiatrists employed in Greater Manchester between September 2015 and November 2017 and is the latest data available.</p><p>NHS Hospital and Community Health Services (HCHS): Child and Adolescent Psychiatrists in Greater Manchester, as at 30 September for each specified year and latest data available, (FTE):</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Child and Adolescent Psychiatrists (FTE)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2015</p></td><td><p>59</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2016</p></td><td><p>59</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2017</p></td><td><p>72</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November 2017</p></td><td><p>75</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em> </em></p><p><em>Source: </em>NHS Digital Monthly Hospital and Community Health Service (HCHS) workforce statistics</p><p>Notes:</p><ol><li>FTE figures are given as this is the most accurate measure of service capacity.</li><li>FTE figures are rounded to the nearest whole number.</li></ol>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-03-27T15:20:29.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862902/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862902/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862902/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-14","Psychiatry: Greater Manchester","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many additional child and adolescent psychiatrists have been recruited by the NHS in Greater Manchester in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL6350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862903","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-28","<p>The remaining costs are made up of a wide variety of expenditure which includes property costs, finance, HR, shared services (transactional processing), procurement, administration, insurance, transport and plant, utilities, and travel. The Environment Agency’s consultation response document will provide more information on the make-up of charges. This is due to be published in March.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-03-28T16:55:26.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862903/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862903/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862903/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-14","Livestock Industry: Licensing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 20 February (HL5471), how the remaining 20 per cent proposed charge for permit variation that does not relate to staff or IT costs is made up.","false","Biography information for Baroness Byford",,"Baroness Byford","HL6351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862904","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-27","<p>When consumers with first generation smart (SMETS1) meters switch energy supplier, if the new supplier is not able to operate the meter in 'smart' mode, the meter will continue to record energy consumption accurately and can be used in 'traditional' mode.</p><p> </p><p>The Data and Communications Company is developing a solution to move SMETS1 meters onto the national communications infrastructure to enable consumers to retain their smart services upon switching. This can be done remotely.</p><p>Second generation smart (SMETS2) meters will be fully compatible between energy providers, therefore allowing all consumers to retain smart services when they switch energy suppliers.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-03-27T12:25:46.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862904/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862904/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862904/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-14","Energy: Meters","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether a smart meter fitted in domestic premises will be replaced free of charge if a householder switches energy supplier to one whose systems are not compatible with its use.","false","Biography information for Baroness Byford",,"Baroness Byford","HL6352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862905","Home Office","false","2018-03-27","<p>On 27 July 2017, the Government commissioned the Migration Advisory Committee (MAC) to gather evidence on patterns of EU migration and the role of migration in the wider economy. It has been asked to report by September 2018 and I understand that the MAC hope to publish an interim report in the near future.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-03-27T15:26:15.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862905/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862905/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862905/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-14","Agriculture: Seasonal Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the answer by Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 28 June 2017 (HL Deb, col 429), when the Migration Advisory Committee will report on the long-term needs of those parts of the agriculture sector that rely on seasonal agricultural workers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Byford",,"Baroness Byford","HL6353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862906","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-28","<p>Any property occupied for domestic purposes will be valued for council tax. Decisions on valuations are a matter for the Valuation Office Agency (VOA).</p><p>Halls of residence which comprise solely of living accommodation or other services used only by residents will be valued for council tax, rather than business rates. Houses in multiple occupation (HMOs) are also subject to council tax, as are dwellings let to university students.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-03-28T14:23:49.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862906/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862906/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862906/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Housing: Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what rules govern council taxes and business rates on (1) blocks of flats for university students, (2) houses in multiple occupation let to university students, and (3) other dwellings let to university students.","false","Biography information for Baroness Byford",,"Baroness Byford","HL6354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862907","Home Office","false","2018-03-27","<p>The available information relates to the number of people attending British citizenship ceremonies in Northern Ireland and is published in Home Office’s <em>Immigration Statistics, October – December 2017</em>, Citizenship table cz_08.</p><p>These figures relate to successful applicants who are required to attend a citizenship ceremony as the final stage of their application and cover the majority of grants. They exclude those not required to attend a ceremony (primarily children under 18 years of age) and unsuccessful applications. Data on applications for British citizenship by the applicant’s place of residence at the time of application are not routinely collated centrally.</p><p>A table of figures for 2014, 2015 and 2016 is provided below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>People attending British citizenship ceremonies in Northern Ireland</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Ceremonies attended</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>595</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>447</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>650</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>Source: Home Office, Migration Border Analysis</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>Immigration Statistics October to December 2017. Subset of data in table cz_08.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Citizenship ceremony figures for 2017 will be published in <em>Immigration Statistics January to March 2018</em> on 24<sup>th</sup> May 2018.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-03-27T15:45:40.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862907/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862907/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862907/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-14","British Nationality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many persons sought British citizenship while resident in Northern Ireland in (1) 2014 to 2015, and (2) 2016 to 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL6355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862908","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-28","<p>We place great value on our close relationship with Ireland and our shared values in relation to fisheries matters, including our strong commitment to sustainable fishing. The Government is engaging regularly with Ireland on these matters. The Fisheries Minister discussed the Voisinage agreement with Michael Creed, the Irish Fisheries Minister, last year.</p><p> </p><p>We will be working to secure the best deal in the negotiations for the whole of the UK fishing industry.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-03-28T16:34:10.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862908/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862908/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862908/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-14","Fisheries: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what conversations they have had with the government of the Republic of Ireland on the rights of Northern Ireland-based fishermen after Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL6356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862909","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-19","<p>The Government recognises that air connectivity between Northern Ireland and the rest of the UK is of the utmost importance given its geographical circumstances. There were over 1.5 million passenger journeys between Belfast Airports and Gatwick and Heathrow Airports in 2016. We expect this demand to continue, given that Northern Ireland is a competitive destination in its own right.</p><p> </p><p>The Government does not frequently consult with British Airways or Aer Lingus about flights between Northern Ireland and London. We believe that air passengers are best served by a commercial airline market which is able to operate in a competitive environment. This allows airlines to determine the routes that they operate, and from which airports, based on their assessment of routes’ viability.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is considering the issue of regional connectivity across the UK as part of developing its future aviation strategy.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-03-19T11:44:55.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862909/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862909/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862909/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-14","Air Routes: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what priority they place on the maintenance of a regular air link between Northern Ireland and London; and how frequently they consult on that issue with (1) British Airways, and (2) Aer Lingus.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL6357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862910","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-28","<p>Ferry services between Northern Ireland and Great Britain are provided commercially by the relevant ferry operators. We would expect those operators to respond to market demand engaging as appropriate with relevant stakeholders and bodies.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-03-28T11:13:06.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862910/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862910/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862910/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-14","Ferries: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the sufficiency of the frequency of sailings of ferry services between Northern Ireland and the UK mainland; and how often such services are reviewed in consultation with the Confederation of British Industry in Northern Ireland and other relevant bodies.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL6358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862911","Home Office","false","2018-03-27","<p>In order to apply for a British passport, a person must first hold a form of British nationality. The predominant form of British nationality in the UK is British Citizenship.</p><p>The current nationality law, the British Nationality Act 1981, defines who is a British citizen. If a person is not automatically a British citizen by birth in the UK or a qualifying territory, then they may be a British citizen by descent. Alternatively, a person can naturalise or register as a British citizen if they meet the relevant statutory requirements.</p><p>The criteria that applies to decisions on whether to grant a British passport, is set out in the written ministerial statement of 25 April 2013. This can be found on Gov.uk.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-03-27T15:22:38.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862911/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862911/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-14","Passports: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government under what circumstances a person born in the Republic of Ireland after 1949, but living in Northern Ireland, can apply for a British passport; and what criteria apply to the decision whether to grant a British passport.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL6359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862912","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-28","<p>Four years since Russia's illegal annexation of Crimea, the human rights situation on the peninsula continues to worsen and access is denied to international human rights organisations. The British Government regularly highlights Russia's illegal annexation, publicly and multilaterally, raising concerns about human rights abuses committed by the de-facto Russian authorities. This includes abuses against the Crimean Tatars. The Foreign Secretary met with representatives of the Crimean Tatars in London on 14 March.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-03-28T16:39:06.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862912/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862912/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-14","Russia: Crimea","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to make representations to the government of Russia regarding reasonable local automony for ethnic and cultural groups in the Crimea, including respect for their traditional institutions, culture and heritage; and whether they will enquire as to any proposals for restoring the previous level of economic activity in the region.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862913","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-22","<p>Help to Buy: Equity Loan has helped 144,826 households buy a new-build home from its launch in April 2013 until September 2017.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-03-22T17:07:17.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862913/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862913/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Help to Buy Scheme","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many homes have been bought with the support of the Help to Buy scheme since April 2013.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL6361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862914","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-28","<p>This data is not currently published due to commercial sensitivity.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-03-28T14:43:06.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862914/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862914/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862914/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Help to Buy Scheme","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what percentage of Help to Buy loans have been repaid before the end of the five year interest free period.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL6362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862915","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-28","<p>The Department’s Energy Trends Table 4.4 includes an extensive monthly breakdown of all gas imports, including liquefied natural gas, by country of origin. Due to the large amount of data in Table 4.4, I have included a copy of it as an attachment:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/682882/ET_4.4.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/682882/ET_4.4.xls</a></p><p>The latest data in Energy Trends is for two months prior to the publication month, and the publication on 29th March will include new data for January 2018.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-03-28T15:40:19.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862915/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862915/answer","Copy of ET_4.4.xls","Copy of ET_4.4.xls","Supplementary info on origin of UK gas imports","Supplementary info on origin of UK gas imports","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862915/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-14","Liquefied Natural Gas: Imports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much liquefied natural gas has been imported into the UK since 1 January; and from which countries.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL6363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862916","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-27","<p>Statistics from the World Steel Association show that 7.5 million tonnes of crude steel was produced in the UK in 2017.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-03-27T12:21:11.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862916/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862916/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-14","Iron and Steel","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much steel was produced in the UK in 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL6364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862917","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-13","<p>We included an assessment of the impact of the proposed expanded London ultra low emission zone (ULEZ) in the analysis carried out as part of the UK plan for tackling roadside nitrogen dioxide concentrations. We published this analysis in the technical report accompanying the plan (see link below). We await the data on the changes to traffic composition and movements since the introduction of the T charge before we can update our assessment on changes to air quality.</p><p>The Government has meaningfully invested to improve air quality in London. London has received directly £137m in funding in support of measures to help improve air quality including the retrofitting of over 1400 buses and the purchase of 34 low emission buses, in addition to the £5.7bn transport settlement to TfL which included provisions to address air quality. Despite this investment and activities undertaken, the Government is concerned that London is not expected to achieve compliance until 2026. We will continue to encourage and support the Mayor to take effective action to address NO2 pollution in the capital.</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/632916/air-quality-plan-technical-report.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/632916/air-quality-plan-technical-report.pdf</a></p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-04-13T12:42:36.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862917/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862917/answer","air-quality-plan-technical-report.pdf","air-quality-plan-technical-report.pdf","Air Quality Plan Technical Report","Air Quality Plan Technical Report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862917/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-14","Air Pollution: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the Mayor of London's plans to reduce air pollution in London.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL6365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862918","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-26","<p>The Secretary of State is now considering the report of the independent inspection of Northamptonshire County Council, including the proposals it makes for the future of local government in Northamptonshire. He has undertaken to make a statement in due course in the Other Place setting out his proposals for next steps.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-03-26T16:59:40.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862918/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862918/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-14","Local Government: Northamptonshire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to take any steps to reorganise local government in Northamptonshire.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL6366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862919","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-03-22","<p>As the Prime Minister has made clear, we are seeking the broadest and deepest possible partnership with the EU – covering more sectors and co-operating more fully than any Free Trade Agreement anywhere in the world today.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government is undertaking a wide range of ongoing analysis in support of our EU exit negotiations and preparations. This work is ongoing, and Ministers have a specific responsibility, which Parliament has endorsed, not to release information that could reveal our negotiating position.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The analysis recently published by the Commons Exiting the EU Committee does not represent Government policy. It is an information gathering exercise, there to test ideas. It is analysis of existing trade relationships - none of which is the outcome we are working towards.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2018-03-22T16:27:03.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862919/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862919/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-03-14","UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what estimate they have made of the impact on GDP of a free trade agreement with the EU compared to membership of the Single Market in each year between 2019 and 2033.","false","Biography information for Lord Livermore",,"Lord Livermore","HL6367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862920","Treasury","false","2018-03-27","<p>The Government is undertaking a wide range of analysis and preparatory work to support our EU exit negotiations and preparations. However, it is not standard practice to provide an ongoing commentary on internal analysis.</p><p> </p><p>Ministers have a specific responsibility, which Parliament has endorsed, not to release information that would undermine our negotiating position.</p><p> </p><p>The analysis recently published by the Commons Exiting the EU Committee does not represent Government policy. It is an information gathering exercise, there to test ideas. It is analysis of existing trade relationships - none of which is the outcome we are working towards.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-03-27T14:02:55.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862920/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862920/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862920/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-14","UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what estimate they have made of the impact on government borrowing of a free trade agreement with the EU compared to membership of the Single Market in each year between 2019 and 2033.","false","Biography information for Lord Livermore",,"Lord Livermore","HL6368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862921","Department for International Trade","false","2018-03-29","<p>The Government is undertaking a wide range of ongoing analysis, in support of our EU exit negotiations and preparations. This work is ongoing, and Ministers have a specific responsibility, which Parliament has endorsed, not to release information that could reveal our negotiating position.</p><p> </p><p>The analysis recently published by the Commons Exiting the EU Committee, does not represent Government policy. It is an information gathering exercise, there to test ideas.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) has provided a qualitative summary of existing literature, on the impacts of signing Free Trade Agreements (FTAs), in the Impact Assessment accompanying the Trade Bill, available here: <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA17-010.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA17-010.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>DIT currently provides impact assessments to Parliament, when EU trade agreements are ratified. The Implementation Period, as agreed at the March European Council, will help to minimise unnecessary disruption for both the UK and EU and provide certainty for businesses and individuals as we move towards our future deep and special partnership with the EU. During the Implementation Period the United Kingdom will be able to negotiate, sign, and ratify new FTAs, which will come into force after the implementation period. As outlined in the White Paper “Preparing for our future trade policy”, we are committed to a transparent approach to international trade, and will ensure Parliament has an appropriate role to play in the scrutiny of new UK trade treaties.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2018-03-29T16:57:43.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862921/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862921/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-03-14","Free Trade: Trade Agreements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, following the publication of the document EU Exit Analysis: Cross-Whitehall Briefing, what assessment they have made of the impact on GDP of new free trade agreements with non-EU countries after Brexit in each year between 2019 and 2033.","false","Biography information for Lord Livermore",,"Lord Livermore","HL6369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862922","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-27","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister has made a clear commitment to protect workers’ rights and the EU (Withdrawal) Bill will ensure that workers’ rights currently enjoyed under EU law will continue to be available in UK law after we have left the EU. The Government has no intention to abolish any EU-derived working time regulations after Brexit.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-03-27T12:22:00.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862922/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862922/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-14","Working Hours: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to abolish all EU-derived working time regulations after Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Livermore",,"Lord Livermore","HL6370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862923","Department for International Trade","false","2018-03-29","<p>The Government is committed to securing continuity of existing EU free trade agreements and other EU preferential arrangements as we leave the EU. We have held discussions on continuity of existing EU trade agreements with more than 70 partner countries, and all have agreed in principle to seek to ensure continuity. It is in no one’s interest to disrupt trade flows, or erect new barriers to trade.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2018-03-29T15:25:21.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862923/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862923/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-03-14","Trade Agreements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many of the 65 non-EU countries with which the UK has trade agreements through membership of the EU have guaranteed that they will continue those agreements on the same terms after Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Livermore",,"Lord Livermore","HL6371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862924","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-27","<p>The UK has committed over £30million to help stabilise liberated areas in Iraq by delivering basic services like water and electricity, rebuilding livelihoods, removing mines and supporting community reconciliation. This will contribute to creating the right conditions for refugees and internally displaced people from across the region to safely return to their areas of origin.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is also financially supporting Jordan, Lebanon and Turkey in meeting the humanitarian needs of the most vulnerable refugees from across the region, including from Iraq, to alleviate pressure on local communities hosting refugees. The UK is committed to ensuring that any refugee returns take place voluntarily in safety and dignity, in line with international law. We work closely with UNHCR, the official agency mandated to lead discussions with Government, and advocate strongly in refugee host countries on this basis. UNHCR estimate that the total registered Iraqi refugee population is currently 152,976 in Turkey; 17,411 in Lebanon and 60,000 in Jordan.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL6373","2018-03-27T16:08:29.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862924/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862924/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862924/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-14","Iraq: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what dialogue they are holding with the governments of (1) Jordan, (2) Lebanon, and (3) Turkey, to ascertain the number of Iraqi refugees hosted by those countries who wish to return to Iraq, and the obstacles stopping those refugees from so doing.","false","Biography information for Lord McInnes of Kilwinning",,"Lord McInnes of Kilwinning","HL6372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862925","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-27","<p>The UK has committed over £30million to help stabilise liberated areas in Iraq by delivering basic services like water and electricity, rebuilding livelihoods, removing mines and supporting community reconciliation. This will contribute to creating the right conditions for refugees and internally displaced people from across the region to safely return to their areas of origin.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is also financially supporting Jordan, Lebanon and Turkey in meeting the humanitarian needs of the most vulnerable refugees from across the region, including from Iraq, to alleviate pressure on local communities hosting refugees. The UK is committed to ensuring that any refugee returns take place voluntarily in safety and dignity, in line with international law. We work closely with UNHCR, the official agency mandated to lead discussions with Government, and advocate strongly in refugee host countries on this basis. UNHCR estimate that the total registered Iraqi refugee population is currently 152,976 in Turkey; 17,411 in Lebanon and 60,000 in Jordan.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL6372","2018-03-27T16:08:30.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862925/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862925/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-14","Iraq: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assistance they are providing to the government of Iraq to allow the safe return of refugees from neighbouring host countries.","false","Biography information for Lord McInnes of Kilwinning",,"Lord McInnes of Kilwinning","HL6373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862926","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-28","<p>We welcome the South African Government's assurance that 'the process of land distribution would be orderly, within South African laws and taking into consideration both the social and economic impact.' We further welcome President Ramaphosa's commitment that land reform will be carried out 'without negatively affecting economic growth, agricultural production and food security' and his assurance that he would 'not allow any smash and grab interventions'.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-03-28T13:45:22.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862926/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862926/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-14","South Africa: Property Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the motion passed in the Parliament of South Africa on 1 March to confiscate land without compensation from white farmers.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbrook",,"Lord Northbrook","HL6374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862927","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-03-21","<p>The Ministry of Defence continually reassesses the Royal Navy's mission in the Strait of Gibraltar, and the assets and people required to deliver it, to ensure that the UK Government's responsibilities can be carried out effectively and can meet evolving threats and future needs. The Royal Navy's Gibraltar Squadron will continue to challenge all incursions into British Gibraltar Territorial Waters. The base infrastructure and the Gibraltar Squadron will continue to be modernised in line with the rest of the Royal Navy.</p><p>We have interpreted visits to be those ships proceeding alongside in Gibraltar. Records show that, over the period 1 September 2017 to 1 March 2018, there were 15 occasions where Royal Navy and Royal Fleet Auxiliary ships visited Gibraltar, in addition to the Gibraltar Squadron that is permanently stationed there.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL6376 ; HL6378","2018-03-21T16:37:59.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862927/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862927/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-03-14","Gibraltar: Navy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the future presence and activity of the Royal Navy in the Strait of Gibraltar.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbrook",,"Lord Northbrook","HL6375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862928","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-03-21","<p>The Ministry of Defence continually reassesses the Royal Navy's mission in the Strait of Gibraltar, and the assets and people required to deliver it, to ensure that the UK Government's responsibilities can be carried out effectively and can meet evolving threats and future needs. The Royal Navy's Gibraltar Squadron will continue to challenge all incursions into British Gibraltar Territorial Waters. The base infrastructure and the Gibraltar Squadron will continue to be modernised in line with the rest of the Royal Navy.</p><p>We have interpreted visits to be those ships proceeding alongside in Gibraltar. Records show that, over the period 1 September 2017 to 1 March 2018, there were 15 occasions where Royal Navy and Royal Fleet Auxiliary ships visited Gibraltar, in addition to the Gibraltar Squadron that is permanently stationed there.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL6375 ; HL6378","2018-03-21T16:37:59.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862928/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862928/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-03-14","Gibraltar: Navy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many Royal Navy visits to Gibraltar have taken place in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbrook",,"Lord Northbrook","HL6376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862929","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-27","<p>The Prime Minister announced a further £20million in humanitarian support and £30million in stabilisation support to the Republic of Iraq during her visit to Baghdad in November 2017. Additionally, at the recent Kuwait Conference for Reconstruction the Minister for the Middle East pledged £1.5 million of new funding for the repair of housing in Mosul through the UN’s Funding Facility for Stabilisation which brings the total number of houses that UK funds will repair to 2,000. The Minister also pledged £8 million of new funding, delivered through UNICEF, to improve the water networks and sanitation facilities for 600,000 people, and to deliver better sanitation in health facilities and schools.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-03-27T16:11:12.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862929/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862929/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862929/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-14","Iraq: Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when the level of UK aid to the Republic of Iraq was last increased.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbrook",,"Lord Northbrook","HL6377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862930","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-03-21","<p>The Ministry of Defence continually reassesses the Royal Navy's mission in the Strait of Gibraltar, and the assets and people required to deliver it, to ensure that the UK Government's responsibilities can be carried out effectively and can meet evolving threats and future needs. The Royal Navy's Gibraltar Squadron will continue to challenge all incursions into British Gibraltar Territorial Waters. The base infrastructure and the Gibraltar Squadron will continue to be modernised in line with the rest of the Royal Navy.</p><p>We have interpreted visits to be those ships proceeding alongside in Gibraltar. Records show that, over the period 1 September 2017 to 1 March 2018, there were 15 occasions where Royal Navy and Royal Fleet Auxiliary ships visited Gibraltar, in addition to the Gibraltar Squadron that is permanently stationed there.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL6375 ; HL6376","2018-03-21T16:37:59.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862930/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862930/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-03-14","Gibraltar: Navy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what are their proposals for future investment in the Royal Navy base in Gibraltar.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbrook",,"Lord Northbrook","HL6378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862931","Department for Education","false","2018-03-28","<p>The Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) has prepared information on students domiciled in England enrolled on foundation degrees, higher national diplomas, or higher national certificates. The figures cover HEFCE-funded higher education institutions and further education colleges in England, as well as enrolments at alternative providers in England. Figures for the academic years 2015/16 and 2016/17 have been provided in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for 2016/17 are provisional, and all figures are valid as of 16 March 2018.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2018-03-28T16:40:32.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862931/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862931/answer","HL6379 Attachment.xlsx","HL6379 Attachment.xlsx","Students_domiciled_in_England_enrolled_FD/HNC/HND","Students_domiciled_in_England_enrolled_FD/HNC/HND","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862931/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Higher Education: Qualifications","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what was the total number of domiciled students in England in (1) 2015–16, and (2) 2016–17, aged (a) 18 to 24, and (b) 25 and over, who were taking (i) full-time foundation degrees, (ii) part-time foundation degrees, (iii) full-time Higher National Certificate (HNC) and Higher National Diploma (HND) courses, and (iv) part-time HNC and HND courses; and of those, how many were studying at further education colleges.","false","Biography information for Lord Smith of Clifton",,"Lord Smith of Clifton","HL6379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862932","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-03-28","<p>The Government set out the UK’s approach to the future security partnership in the Foreign Policy, Defence and Development paper of September 2017. The Prime Minister further expanded on this most recently in her Munich speech on 17th February.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government has committed to hold a vote on the final deal in Parliament as soon as possible after the negotiations have concluded. This vote will cover both the Withdrawal Agreement and the terms of our future relationship.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2018-03-28T15:41:35.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862932/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862932/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862932/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-03-14","UK Relations with EU: Security","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 20 February (HL5442) concerning the future security partnership with the EU, whether they intend to consult Parliament on those proposals; and whether Parliament will be asked to give final approval.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL6380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862933","Treasury","false","2018-03-27","<p>The government takes a balanced approach to government spending, getting debt falling but also investing in our key public services like the NHS, and keeping taxes low. It also believes that the UK has a moral obligation to the world’s poorest, and the UK will continue to keep its promise to spend 0.70 per cent of Gross National Income on Official Development Assistance (ODA). This represents less than 2 per cent of total public spending.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-03-27T12:31:00.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862933/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862933/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-14","Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 16 February (HL5444), what assessment they have made of the compatibility of the UK's commitment to spend 0.79 per cent of Gross National Income on overseas aid with cuts in spending for other public services.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL6381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862934","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-20","<p>DFID does not make such estimates. However, data on the different percentages of Official Development Assistance of Gross National Income is published openly by the OECD, and is available with this link <a href="http://www.oecd.org/dac/financing-sustainable-development/development-finance-data/ODA-2016-detailed-summary.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.oecd.org/dac/financing-sustainable-development/development-finance-data/ODA-2016-detailed-summary.pdf</a>. The UK Government is committed to spending 0.7% of Gross National Income on Aid as set out in the International Development (Official Development Assistance Target) Act 2015.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-03-20T16:24:25.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862934/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862934/answer","ODA-2016-detailed-summary.pdf","ODA-2016-detailed-summary.pdf","Detailed ODA Summary - 2016","Detailed ODA Summary - 2016","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862934/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-14","Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what estimate they have made of the savings that would be made if UK aid spending were based on the world average percentage spend for overseas aid.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL6382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862935","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-03-28","<p>We have made rapid progress on the Withdrawal Agreement from the EU, agreeing the majority of the legal text including all of the chapters on the implementation period, citizens’ rights and the financial settlement­.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>We will carry this momentum forward as we work to agree the remaining areas and conclude the Withdrawal Agreement by October 2018, before we leave the EU at the end of March 2019.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2018-03-28T11:13:49.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862935/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862935/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862935/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-03-14","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the likelihood of finalising a UK–EU Brexit agreement by October 2018; and if such an agreement were reached, whether the date of withdrawal will be brought forward.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL6383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862936","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-27","<p>In December 2017 Government announced up to £44m, over the next 3 years, for the Advanced Modular Reactor (AMR) Programme. The aim of this programme is to assess the feasibility of innovative reactor projects and to accelerate development of promising designs. Government also announced up to £12m for the UK Regulators to increase their capability and capacity to assess and license new designs.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has committed to phasing out electricity generation using unabated coal by 2025. It is unlikely that any small modular reactor nuclear plants would be operational in the UK by this date. However, several small reactor developers have expressed an interest in entering the UK Generic Design Assessment (GDA) process in the near future. GDA is a process that enables regulators to assess new nuclear reactor designs in advance of an application to build a reactor at a specific site.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-03-27T12:23:03.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862936/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862936/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-14","Nuclear Power Stations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what investment they are making in the research and development of small modular nuclear plants; and how many small modular nuclear plants will be operational when all coal-fired power stations are phased out.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL6384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862937","Attorney General","false","2018-03-28","<p>As at 28 February 2018 the Crown Prosecution Service employed (1) 2,083 men and (2) 3,987 women. In senior posts (graded at Senior Civil Service or equivalent) the Crown Prosecution Service employed (a) 34 men and (b) 40 women, with women making up 54% of the workforce in these grades.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2018-03-28T11:12:01.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862937/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862937/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862937/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-03-14","Crown Prosecution Service","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many (1) men, and (2) women, are employed by the Crown Prosecution Service; and how many (a) men, and (b) women, hold senior posts.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL6385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862938","Department for Education","false","2018-03-21","<p>Private colleges offering higher education degrees can participate in the Teaching Excellence and Student Outcomes Framework (TEF) if they meet the eligibility requirements. From the 2019-20 academic year, TEF will be a condition of registration for providers with more than 500 students on higher education courses. Smaller providers, for whom the cost of participation might be disproportionate, may participate on a voluntary basis if they meet the eligibility criteria.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","HL6329","2018-03-21T17:58:39.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862938/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862938/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862938/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Higher Education: Private Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether private colleges that offer higher education degrees will be rated as gold, silver or bronze in the same way as universities.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL6386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862939","Department for Education","false","2018-03-28","<p>The department does not provide specific guidance on the recruitment of members, but as members are responsible for the appointment of trustees, it is important that they understand the skills, behaviours and knowledge that trustees need to deliver effective governance.</p><p>Guidance sets out that members may be appointed by special resolution by existing members or the foundation or sponsor of the multi-academy trust (MAT).</p><p>The guidance is attached and available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/governance-handbook" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/governance-handbook</a>.</p><p>The articles of association of each individual trust set out the specific arrangements for the appointment of members to each trust.</p><p>Companies House specify their own requirements for MATs, as companies limited by guarantee, with regard to appointments and resignations. It is for individual MATs to ensure they follow these requirements.</p><p>There is no requirement for MATs to publish the minutes of meetings of members and trustees. However, the department’s Model Articles of Association state that the trust board must, as soon as is reasonably practicable, make available for inspection by any interested person, copies of the agenda, signed minutes of every such meeting and any report or other paper considered at such meeting.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","HL6388 ; HL6389","2018-03-28T14:00:09.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862939/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862939/answer","Governance_Handbook_-_January_2017.pdf","Governance_Handbook_-_January_2017.pdf","Governance Handbook","Governance Handbook","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/862939/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-14","Academies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what guidance is provided to Multi-Academy Trusts on the appointment of members.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL6387"
